TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rational and Social Theories as Complementary Explanations of Communication Media Choices: Two Policy-Capturing Studies
AU  - Webster, Jane
AU  - Trevino, Linda Klebe
Y1  - 1995/12/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256843
DO  - 10.5465/256843
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1544
EP  - 1572
VL  - 38
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Recent media choice research has focused on attempts to determine what theory best explains people's choices of communication media. Two within-subject policy-capturing studies support the notion that media richness and social influence theories are complementary rather than competing and that the relative importance of choice factors depends on the medium. A comparison of policy-capturing and survey findings points to policy capturing as a useful research methodology. Results also suggest that rational and social factors should be included in comprehensive models of media choice that address both traditional and new media.
AB  - Recent media choice research has focused on attempts to determine what theory best explains people's choices of communication media. Two within-subject policy-capturing studies support the notion that media richness and social influence theories are complementary rather than competing and that the relative importance of choice factors depends on the medium. A comparison of policy-capturing and survey findings points to policy capturing as a useful research methodology. Results also suggest that rational and social factors should be included in comprehensive models of media choice that address both traditional and new media.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256843
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256843
Y2  - 2026/04/24
